Definition 5.5. Let $F$ be a functor between two weak cofibration categories. Then $F$ is called a weak left Quillen functor if $F$ commutes with finite colimits and preserves cofibrations and trivial cofibrations.
Definition 2.3. Let $p:I\to J$ be a functor between small categories. The functor $p$ is said to be (right) cofinal if for every $j$ in $J$ the over category ${p}_{j/}$ is nonempty and connected.
Definition 5.18. A map $X\to Y$ in $\mathcal{S}_{f}$ will be called: 1. A cofibration, if it is one to one (at every degree). 2. A weak equivalence, if the induced map of geometric realizations: $|X|\to|Y|$ is a weak equivalence of topological spaces.
Definition 2.11. An almost model category is a quadruple $(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{W},\mathcal{F},\mathcal{C})$ satisfying all the axioms of a model category, except (maybe) the two out of three property for $\mathcal{W}$. More precisely, an almost model category satisfies: 1. $\mathcal{M}$ is complete and cocomplete. 2. $\mathcal{W}$ is a class of morphisms in $\mathcal{M}$ that is closed under retracts. 3. $\mathcal{F},\mathcal{C}$ are subcategories of $\mathcal{M}$ that are closed under retracts. 4. $\mathcal{C}\cap\mathcal{W}\subseteq{}^{\perp}\mathcal{F}$ and $\mathcal{C}\subseteq{}^{\perp}(\mathcal{F}\cap\mathcal{W})$. 5. There exist functorial factorizations in $\mathcal{M}$ into a map in $\mathcal{C}\cap\mathcal{W}$ followed by a map in $\mathcal{F}$ and into a map in $\mathcal{C}$ followed by a map in $\mathcal{F}\cap\mathcal{W}$.
Definition 5.12. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a monoidal almost model category, and let $\mathcal{C}$ be an almost model category category which is also tensored over $\mathcal{M}$. We say that $\mathcal{C}$, with this structure, is an $\mathcal{M}$-enriched almost model category, if $(-)\otimes(-):\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ is a left Quillen bifunctor (see Definition 5.1). We denote the two variable adjunction of $\otimes$ by $(\otimes,\operatorname{Map},\hom)$. Note that $\operatorname{Map}(-,-):\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})^{op}\times% \operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})\to\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{M}),$ $\hom(-,-):\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{M})^{op}\times\operatorname{Ind}(% \mathcal{C})\to\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C}).$
Definition 4.5. Let $(\mathcal{M},\otimes,I)$ be a monoidal category and let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category. A left action of $\mathcal{M}$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is a bifunctor $\otimes:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ together with coherent natural isomorphisms $L\otimes(K\otimes X)\cong(K\otimes L)\otimes X,$ $I\otimes X\cong X,$ for $X$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and $K,L$ in $\mathcal{M}$. If we say that $\mathcal{C}$ is tensored over $\mathcal{M}$ we mean that we are given a left action of $\mathcal{M}$ on $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 5.22. 1. A simplicial weak cofibration category is just an $\mathcal{S}_{f}$-enriched weak cofibration category (see Definition 5.16). 2. A simplicial almost model category is just an $\mathcal{S}$-enriched almost model category (see Definition 5.12).
Definition 5.1. Let $\mathcal{B}$,$\mathcal{C}$,$\mathcal{D}$ be almost model categories and let $(-)\otimes(-):\mathcal{B}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a bifunctor. The bifunctor $\otimes$ is called a left Quillen bifunctor if $\otimes$ is a part of a two variable adjunction $(\otimes,\operatorname{Hom}_{r},\operatorname{Hom}_{l})$ (see Definition 4.1), and for every cofibration $j:X\to Y$ in $\mathcal{B}$ and every cofibration $i:L\to K$ in $\mathcal{C}$ the induced map $X\otimes K\coprod_{X\otimes L}Y\otimes L\to Y\otimes K$ is a cofibration (in $\mathcal{D}$), which is acyclic if either $i$ or $j$ is.
Definition 2.14. A weak cofibration category $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{W},\mathcal{C}of)$ is called 1. ind-admissible, if the class $\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(\mathcal{W})$, of morphisms in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$, satisfies the two out of three property. 2. almost ind-admissible, if the class $\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(\mathcal{W})$, of morphisms in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$, satisfies the following portion of the two out of three property: For every pair $X\xrightarrow{f}Z\xrightarrow{g}Y$ of composable morphisms in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$ we have: (a) If $f,g$ belong to $\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(\mathcal{W})$ then $g\circ f\in\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(\mathcal{W})$. (b) If $f,g\circ f$ belong to $\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(\mathcal{W})$ then $g\in\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(\mathcal{W})$.
Definition 2.6. A cofinite poset is a poset $T$ such that for every element $x$ in $T$ the set $T_{x}:=\{z\in T|z\leq x\}$ is finite.
Definition 2.1. A category $I$ is called filtered if the following conditions are satisfied: 1. The category $I$ is non-empty. 2. For every pair of objects $s,t\in I$, there exists an object $u\in I$, together with morphisms $s\to u$ and $t\to u$. 3. For every pair of morphisms $f,g:s\to t$ in $I$, there exists a morphism $h:t\to u$ in $I$ such that $h\circ f=h\circ g$.
